        <h3 class="cag-h3">How Well Do Congo African Greys Actually Talk?</h3>
        <p>Congo African Greys are widely considered the best talking parrots on earth, routinely learning 100+ words and using them in context rather than parroting at random. That contextual ability — asking for a food by name, greeting a specific person — is what sets a Congo apart from birds that merely repeat sounds.</p>
        <img class="sec-img og-photo" src={IMG + "congo-african-grey-head-scratch-bonding.webp"} srcset={IMG + "congo-african-grey-head-scratch-bonding-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "congo-african-grey-head-scratch-bonding.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="A Congo African Grey leaning into a gentle head scratch from Mark, showing the bond hand-raising builds" />

        <h4 class="cag-h4">At What Age Does a Congo Start Talking?</h4>
        <p>Most Congo African Greys begin mimicking sounds and first words around 6–12 months and hit their stride between one and two years, though every bird runs its own timeline. Because talking grows from trust, an early-socialized, hand-raised chick tends to find its voice sooner than a stressed or under-handled bird.</p>

        <h5 class="cag-h5">Our Hand-Raising and Daily Socialization Build Early Vocabulary</h5>
        <p>We talk to, handle and name-train our chicks every single day, which front-loads the word-to-meaning associations a Congo needs. That daily groundwork is why our buyers so often report first words within weeks of homecoming — the foundation was laid here before the bird ever left.</p>

        <h3 class="cag-h3">How Do You Identify a True Congo — Red Tail, Grey Body, White Mask?</h3>
        <p>A true Congo African Grey is unmistakable once you know the marks: a light silver-grey scalloped body, a solid bright-red tail, a bare white face mask, a black beak, and pale yellow adult eyes. Those exact features are what our species photos show, and they're the first thing to check against any listing's pictures.</p>
        <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/congo-african-grey-red-tail-comparison-hero.webp" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Close-up of a Congo African Grey's defining bright red tail against silver-grey plumage" />

        <h4 class="cag-h4">Should You Choose a Congo or a Timneh?</h4>
        <p>Congos are larger with a brighter red tail and the headline vocabulary, while Timnehs are smaller, maroon-tailed, and often calmer and earlier to talk — both are wonderful, and the right pick is about your home, not prestige. Our full <a href="/congo-vs-timneh-african-grey/">Congo vs Timneh African Grey comparison</a> weighs size, temperament, talking and price so you can choose with your eyes open, and our <a href="/timneh-african-grey-for-sale/">Timneh African Greys for sale</a> are listed separately.</p>
