        <h2 class="cag-h2">Can You Legally Own a Congo African Grey in the USA?</h2>
        <p>Yes — our Congos are captive-bred, which makes them fully legal to keep and rehome across state lines once the paperwork is in order. The species sits on CITES Appendix I, and rather than tiptoe around that, we put it front and centre: Appendix I is the very line that divides documented breeders like us from the wild-caught trade we will never touch.</p>
        <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/buy-an-african-grey-safely-checklist-infographic.webp" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Checklist infographic for buying a captive-bred African Grey safely and legally under CITES" />

        <h3 class="cag-h3">What Does CITES Appendix I Mean for a Buyer?</h3>
        <p>CITES Appendix I is the strictest protection tier, and for a buyer it simply means captive-bred documentation is essential — which is why it rides on every bird we place. Set it alongside our USDA Animal Welfare Act license and you're holding a documentation trail no fake listing can reproduce. Our <a href="/captive-bred-african-grey-parrot/">captive-bred African Grey program</a> explains how that paperwork is generated.</p>

        <h4 class="cag-h4">Is It Legal to Ship a Captive-Bred African Grey Between States?</h4>
        <p>Domestic, state-to-state transfer of a captive-bred, documented African Grey is legal with the proper paperwork, which is exactly how our birds travel. What's not legal is international shipment of an Appendix-I parrot on a casual basis — and that distinction matters when you're reading listings.</p>

        <h5 class="cag-h5">Captive-Bred Appendix-I Birds Are Legal to Own and Transfer Domestically With Paperwork</h5>
        <p><a href="https://www.parrots.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The World Parrot Trust</a> explains how ethical captive breeding takes poaching pressure off wild African Grey flocks — a principle we hold without exception: every Congo we sell was hatched in the USA to captive parents and moves legally inside the country with its CITES and USDA records. Our <a href="/cites-african-grey-documentation/">CITES documentation guide</a> walks through each one.</p>

        <h6 class="cag-h6">We Do Not Ship Internationally — Anyone Offering to Is Breaking CITES Law</h6>
        <p>For the record, we do not ship African Greys internationally, full stop. Because the African Grey was uplisted to <a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/appendices.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CITES Appendix I</a> at CoP17, with the tighter rules taking hold in January 2017, any seller casually offering "worldwide shipping" of a Congo is advertising something the Convention forbids — a scam tell dressed up as a service.</p>
        <div class="sec-cta">
          <a class="btn-clay" href="#reserve">Ask about CITES paperwork &rarr;</a>
          <a class="btn-ghost" href="/cites-african-grey-documentation/">Read the documentation guide</a>
        </div>
